body:
Im not sure yet it covers all issues yet. As mentioned "start_date" is now compared against utc which in case of a different timezone will lead to unexpected results from the user's perspective.

It also begs the question why are we using UTC at all and why dont we leave it to the system to determine what the right time is. The only case I can imagine that you want to do this if you have your boxes spread around multiple regions.

@aoen @mistercrunch @artwr @jlowin what do you guys think?

@bolkedebruin 

> As you are using threading (which is cooperative) and not multiprocessing the issue will remain the same for dags that are difficult to parse or am I incorrect?

No, threading is preemptive, I tested to confirm by adding a dag that never finishes parsing into the dag folder while the webserver is up. The webserver continues to respond to handle requests and only the background thread is blocked on parsing.

@bolkedebruin 

> In addition in increases the chances of a state mismatch between the scheduler and webserver (now suddenly the webserver can have newer definitions than the scheduler, who has what?)

This can already happen now, if gunicorn decides to restart the webserver when the webserver has newer definitions than the scheduler.

@plypaul 

> Now that the SCHEDULED state has been introduced, tasks start out in the SCHEDULED state and once the task is sent to the executor, it is set to the QUEUED state.

is it your intention to have QUEUED being set by the executor and not by the scheduler? Now the scheduler seems to set two different exit states for TaskInstances (actually 3 with UP_FOR_RETRY).
